I only reboot the PC about once a week, and my wireless Chromebook worked OK accessing weatherbug.
The first thing I did was to clear Firefox’s cache &
column2: cookies. That let weatherbug’s first page load, but I could not navigate, &amp
column3: clicking on its different options just gave a spinning circle. Closing &amp
column4: reopening Firefox gave the 502 Bad Gateway message again. IOW clearing cache &amp
column5: cookies was good for a one time only first page load of weatherbug. All following attempts gave the 502 message.

column1: I rebooted the modem &
column2: router but that made no difference. I didn’t expect it to because the Chromebook worked, but I figured why not give it a try anyway.

column1: I then rebooted the PC and that solved the problem.

1266419,2019-08-09 16:04:40 -0800,2019-08-10T14:52:59Z,"Firefox gives a ""Firefox already running"" error despite reinstalling repeatedly","

The version I've installed recently is v68.0.1 (x64), my OS is WIndows 7.
This error began after my PC suffered a significant error that crashed out most active programs, including Firefox
column2: attempting to start Firefox again caused the relatively common ""Firefox is already running but is not responding. The old process must be closed to open a new window"" error to pop p, with the options ""Close Process"" and ""Cancel"". Clicking either button caused the error message to become unresponsive, and after a few minutes a second identical error would pop up (without the original one ever closing)
column3: sometimes when there were several unresponsive errors it would sometimes crash Windows Explorer if I tried to interact with new popups. In Task manager there were multiple Firefox processes running, but attempting to ""End Process"" would not end two of them, they simply stayed there active. By this point I'd resolved all other issues from the PC crash, as far as I could see, and no other programs were showing any issues at all.

column1: I restarted the PC several times but the error persisted
column2: I was able to create a new profile in Profile Manager but this did not stop the error. I uninstalled Firefox and manually deleted the parent.lock files in the Appdata/Roaming/Mozilla/Firefox/Profiles folder (they were 'in use by Firefox' if I didn't uninstall and restart the PC first, even though no Firefox processes were listed as running in Task Manager). I then reinstalled Firefox, but I still got the same error popup (though it at least didn't become unresponsive and crash Windows Explorer any more - but I still have the un-ending processes in Task Manager).

column1: By this point I've (after backing them up!) uninstalled Firefox and manually deleted everything Firefox-related in the Appdata/Roaming folder, everything Firefox-related in the Appdata/Local folder, and under Program Files (X86), then reinstalled Firefox again. The error persists, unchanged.
Any further suggestions on what I could try would be welcome, I'm stumped by this. Chrome and Avast Browser work fine
column2: Internet Explorer works about as well as it ever does. No new programs had been installed around the time of the problem (to my knowledge) and I've been using Firefox for years on this PC.

column1: ",desktop

1266208,2019-08-05 21:15:42 -0800,2019-08-06T13:44:23Z,Adobe Acrobat Pro DC's 'Attach to Email' returns error if .PDF file is opened via Firefox's download library.,"

Adobe Acrobat: 2015.006.30498
Firefox 68.0.1 64-bit
Windows 10 1803

The issue: When a user downloads a .PDF file with Firefox and opens the file via the 'downloads library' it opens the file in Adobe Acrobat Pro DC. When the user then attempts to use the 'Attach to Email' function in Acrobat, it returns the error ""the file ""[location of users Outlook .OST file]"" is in use and cannot be accessed. Close any application that is using this file, and then try again. You might need to restart the computer.

The issue does not present itself if the .PDF file, downloaded via Firefox is opened from the 'File Explorer' download folder. (EG by clicking the corresponding 'folder' icon next to the download, then opening the .PDF file from there or by any other means of accessing the file in question through File Explorer)
There are also no issues downloading .PDF files and attaching them in the same manner, using other browsers or their versions of the download manager. (IE, Edge, Chrome)
This issue has appeared on two computers tested so far and is repeatable/persistent.

I suspect that the message regarding the .OST file is a bit of a red herring. I think the FF downloads library window is somehow locking the PDF opened through it and thus causing an error when attempting to pass the file over to Outlook to send as an attachment.
Any assistance regarding this would be appreciated.
